data.content:
Here's the performance analysis for `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`. Given the stated context — millions of log entries/minute — all code in this file is on a hot path.

---

### Scan Execution Checklist

| Recipe | Hits |
|--------|------|
| `.IndexOf` without `StringComparison` | 0 |
| `.Substring(` | 0 |
| `.StartsWith/.EndsWith` without `StringComparison` | 0 |
| Sync-over-async | 0 |
| `.ToLower()/.ToUpper()` | 0 |
| `new Regex(` | 0 |
| Chained `.Replace` 3+ | 0 |
| `.ToLowerInvariant()` | 1 |
| `params` arrays | 2 |
| LINQ operators (`.Select/.Where/.Take/.Aggregate/.Any`) | 16 |
| `.ToList()` | 1 |
| `.ToArray()` | 3 |
| `new List<` (per-call) | 1 |
| `Enumerable.Reverse` / `Enum.GetValues` | 2 |
| Unsealed classes | 1 of 3 (2 static) |
| Sealed classes | 0 |

---

### Findings

#### 1. LINQ Chains on Every Call — 16 Instances 🔴

**Impact:** Each `Humanize` call allocates 3–6 enumerator objects + delegate closures. At millions of calls/min, this is severe GC pressure.
**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L128, L140, L143, L146, L149, L158, L169, L244, L261-262, L270-272, L284, L304`

**Fix:** Replace LINQ chains with `foreach` loops writing into stack-allocated or pooled buffers. Specific chains:

`SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan` (L133–149) — 3 enumerators + list allocation:
```csharp
private static void SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    List<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    int kept = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < timeParts.Count; i++)
    {
        bool isNonNull = timeParts[i] != null;
        if (!countEmptyUnits && !isNonNull)
        {
            timeParts[i] = null;
            continue;
        }
        if (kept >= precision)
        {
            timeParts[i] = null;
            continue;
        }
        kept++;
        if (countEmptyUnits && !isNonNull)
            timeParts[i] = null;
    }
}
```

`IsContainingOnlyNullValue` (L127–128) — enumerator + delegate:
```csharp
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(List<string?> timeParts)
{
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
        if (part != null) return false;
    return true;
}
```

`ConcatenateTimeSpanParts` (L155–171) — `.Where().ToList()` + `.Take()`:
```csharp
private static string ConcatenateTimeSpanParts(
    List<string?> timeSpanParts, CultureInfo culture, string collectionSeparator)
{
    // Count non-null parts and build result directly
    int nonNullCount = 0;
    foreach (var p in timeSpanParts)
        if (p != null) nonNullCount++;

    if (nonNullCount == 0) return "no time";

    var sb = new StringBuilder();
    int index = 0;
    foreach (var p in timeSpanParts)
    {
        if (p == null) continue;
        index++;
        if (index > 1 && index < nonNullCount)
            sb.Append(collectionSeparator);
        else if (index == nonNullCount && nonNullCount > 1)
            sb.Append(" and ");
        sb.Append(p);
    }
    return sb.ToString();
}
```

`HumanizeDisplayStrings` (L266–286) — `.Select().Where().ToArray()`:
```csharp
private string HumanizeDisplayStrings(IEnumerable<string?> strings, string separator)
{
    var items = new List<string>();
    foreach (var item in strings)
    {
        if (item == null) continue;
        var trimmed = item.AsSpan().Trim();
        if (trimmed.Length > 0)
            items.Add(trimmed.ToString());
    }
    // ... same join logic
}
```

---

#### 2. `enum.ToString().ToLowerInvariant()` Per Call 🟡

**Impact:** `Enum.ToString()` allocates a string + reflection lookup on every call; `.ToLowerInvariant()` allocates a second string. Called once per time unit per log entry.
**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L175`
**Fix:** Cache the lowercase names in a static array or dictionary:

```csharp
private static readonly string[] s_unitNames =
[
    "year", "month", "week", "day", "hour", "minute", "second", "millisecond"
];

private static string FormatTimePart(int value, TimeUnit unit, CultureInfo culture)
{
    var unitName = s_unitNames[(int)unit];
    return value == 1 ? $"{value} {unitName}" : $"{value} {unitName}s";
}
```

---

#### 3. `params IStringTransformer[]` Array Allocation 🟡

**Impact:** Allocates a `T[]` on every call, even for the common 1-transformer case.
**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L303`
**Fix:** Add a 1-argument overload: `Transform(this string input, CultureInfo culture, IStringTransformer t) => t.Transform(input);`

---

#### 4. `new List<string?>(8)` Allocated Per Call in `CreateTimeParts` 🟡

**Impact:** Heap allocation on every `Humanize` call. With millions of calls/min, this adds up.
**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L91`
**Fix:** Use a `Span<string?>` with `stackalloc` (8 elements max) or accept a caller-provided buffer. Alternatively, use a value-type builder pattern.

---

#### 5. Static `TimeUnits` Array Uses `Enumerable.Reverse` + Spread 🟡

**Impact:** One-time cost at startup — not a hot-path issue, but unnecessarily complex.
**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L41`
**Fix:** Replace with a literal reversed array:
```csharp
private static readonly TimeUnit[] TimeUnits =
    [TimeUnit.Millisecond, TimeUnit.Second, TimeUnit.Minute, TimeUnit.Hour,
     TimeUnit.Day, TimeUnit.Week, TimeUnit.Month, TimeUnit.Year];
```

---

#### 6. `DefaultCollectionFormatter` Not Sealed ℹ️

**Impact:** Prevents JIT devirtualization of `virtual` methods (`Humanize` overloads). 1 of 1 non-static class is unsealed.
**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L208`
**Fix:** Add `sealed` keyword: `public sealed class DefaultCollectionFormatter`
**Caveat:** Only if no subclasses exist elsewhere. The `virtual` methods suggest it may be designed for inheritance — verify before sealing.

---

### Positive Practices
- ✅ No sync-over-async patterns
- ✅ No `new Regex()` per call
- ✅ No `HttpClient` misuse
- ✅ `List<string?>` pre-sized with capacity 8 (L91)
- ✅ No `string.Format` boxing — uses interpolation

---

### Summary

| Severity | Count | Top Issue |
|----------|-------|-----------|
| 🔴 Critical | 1 | LINQ chains allocating 3–6 objects per call on hot path (16 sites) |
| 🟡 Moderate | 4 | `enum.ToString()` caching, `params` overload, per-call list, static init |
| ℹ️ Info | 1 | Unsealed class |

> ⚠️ **Disclaimer:** These results are generated by an AI assistant and are non-deterministic. Findings may include false positives, miss real issues, or suggest changes that are incorrect for your specific context. Always verify recommendations with benchmarks and human review before applying changes to production code.
